<br>
Actually ITS NOT. But of course, no one has ever bothered to run some serious 'scientific' statistics on that. I am not going to deny that there is a huge subjective part in those observations, but too many have been reporting this to make me suspect there might actually be some truth in there.<br>
<br>
Let's make a few assumptions.<br>
<br>
* the random generator used for the /random command calls up the same (or a similar) code as all the other rolls made in the game mechanics<br>
* the random generator is a custom optimisation and uses some programming short-cuts on a number series of supposedly very low frequency<br>
* the programmer who did the implementation was not a random generation expert and never really bothered to really run statistics on his creation.<br>
<br>
Here's the experiment :<br>
run /random 1000 about 10 millions times and parse the data. then run a frequency analysis. <br>
<br>
I can GUARANTEE you will isolate medium frequency patterns and possibly even some high frequency ones, depending ont the quality of the implementation. That would explain why people tend to have 5 fizzles in a row then none for the next day.<br>
<br>
Assuming that every action in the game has an equal statistical chance of success is not a good idea... And I suspect that the implementation of the random generator skews the probabilities VERY significantly. But then again... I have never bothered to parse such logs.<br>
<br>
Assume the worse and have your contingency plans, because shit WILL hit the fan...<br>
<br>
<br>
